The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Bengal | College shut by violence
                                                                                                                     4                                                                                      College shut by violence
          A STAFF REPORTER                                     
	Calcutta, Dec. 19: A college in Behala shut down four days before its winter break because of students violence, amid reports of tension and turmoil from several other campuses.        
	Things are just not right for the college to function. We have closed down the college, though efforts are on to reopen as early as possible, said Behala College principal Swapan Kumar Sur.         
	Nearly 200 alleged members of the Trinamul Congress students wing had ransacked Surs office and smashed furniture in classrooms and laboratories yesterday.         
	The glass panels of cabinets containing important files have been smashed. Im not sure if the papers are in place. The laboratories have also been damaged, Sur said.         
	About 2km away, supporters of the Trinamul Chhatra Parishad and the CPM students wing, the SFI, clashed at Sarsuna College today after a student was barred from depositing tuition fees past the deadline.         
	Students who want to contest college elections have to first clear their dues.         
	Bombs and stones flew outside Maharaja Srishchandra College on Bhupen Bose Avenue yesterday. Trinamul has bagged 35 of the 46 seats in the college union and dislodged the SFI after two decades.        
	Blasts and gunshots had also rung out near Naba Ballygunge Mahavidyalaya  formerly Charuchandra College  in Kasba when Trinamul students demanded that the results of the nomination paper scrutiny be declared immediately.         
	Whats happening on college campuses is unfortunate, Naba Ballygunge principal Sukamal Datta said.        
	Education minister Sudarshan Ray Chaudhuri blamed outsiders for the incidents.         
	Mamata Banerjee put the blame on polices partisan role. She also accused college principals of acting at the behest of the CPM and dismissing nominations of Trinamul students unions.         
	Trinamul won the elections to a slew of colleges in Hooghly and and Burdwan amid allegations of browbeating rivals. Massive police arrangements have been made for a slew college polls to be held in Burdwan tomorrow.                                                                                                                                                             
